language Essence 1.3

$ Social Golfers Problem — Formulation 6: Set of Sets of Sets (Nested Sets)
$
$ Domain:  set (size w) of set (size g) of set (size s) of Golfers
$
$ Information carried by the domain:
$   - Cardinalities at each nesting level: w weeks, g groups, s golfers
$   - Set semantics at each level: no duplicate weeks, no duplicate groups
$     within a week, no duplicate golfers within a group
$
$ Information NOT carried (must be constrained explicitly):
$   - Disjointness of groups within a week (groups can overlap without constraint)
$   - Coverage: every golfer appears each week
$   Together these form the partition constraint.
$
$ Explicit constraints needed:
$   1. Partition constraint: groups within each week partition all golfers
$   2. Pairing constraint: no pair of golfers shares a group more than once
$
$ Compared to Formulation 5 (matrix of sets):
$   - No indexing at all — everything is nested sets.
$   - Week ordering and group ordering are both eliminated by set semantics,
$     removing those symmetries from the search space.
$   - The trade-off: quantification uses set membership rather than array indexing.

given w, g, s : int(1..)

letting nGolfers be g * s
letting Golfers be new type of size nGolfers

find sched : set (size w) of set (size g) of set (size s) of Golfers

$ Partition constraint: within each week, groups are pairwise disjoint.
$ With g groups of size s and g*s golfers, disjointness implies coverage.
such that
    forAll week in sched .
        forAll group1 in week .
            forAll group2 in week .
                group1 != group2 -> |group1 intersect group2| = 0,

$ Pairing constraint: no two golfers share a group more than once
such that
    forAll p1 : Golfers .
        forAll p2 : Golfers .
            p1 != p2 ->
            (sum week in sched .
                sum group in week .
                    toInt(p1 in group /\ p2 in group)
            ) <= 1
